Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome to our 24th Weekly Dose of Optimism. This will be =
our final Weekly Dose of 2022 as we take some time off to refresh over the =
holiday. 2022 has been a year of ups and downs (although, the same could be=
 said of literally every year ever), but we=E2=80=99re glad that this last =
edition of the year is filled with some pretty massive ups.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Not Boring
It=E2=80=99s the most wonderful time of the year: planning out our Q1 2023 =
content and sponsor calendar, of course.=20
If you=E2=80=99re interested in reaching all of the smart, curious people h=
ere by sponsoring The Weekly Dose of Optimism, Monday essays, or Not Boring=
 Founder=E2=80=99s podcast just reply to this email or email us directly at=
 partnerships@notboring.co.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
(1) DOE National Laboratory Makes History by Achieving Fusion Ignition [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/c479e501-149c-49fb-82c1-d6a0b46b0274?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From The Department of Energy
The U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) and DOE=E2=80=99s National Nuclear Secu=
rity Administration (NNSA) today announced the achievement of fusion igniti=
on at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL)=E2=80=94a major scienti=
fic breakthrough decades in the making that will pave the way for advanceme=
nts in national defense and the future of clean power. On December 5, a tea=
m at LLNL=E2=80=99s National Ignition Facility (NIF) conducted the first co=
ntrolled fusion experiment in history to reach this milestone, also known a=
s scientific energy breakeven, meaning it produced more energy from fusion =
than the laser energy used to drive it.
Fusion ignition! We=E2=80=99ve been able to create nuclear fusion for a whi=
le now, but this is the first ever recorded positive net energy reaction fr=
om nuclear fusion. This reaction had a Q factor of 1.5. Q>1 has been the ho=
ly grail of nuclear fusion for decades =E2=80=94 it means you get more ener=
gy from a reaction than you put into it. Previously, nuclear fusion was gre=
at and all, but it wasn=E2=80=99t a viable source of clean energy when you =
put in Q and get back Q-1. It didn=E2=80=99t scale, but now it might. =20
Scaling and commercializing Q>1 nuclear fusion is likely the most realistic=
 path towards living in a world of free, clean, and abundant energy. It=E2=
=80=99s also probably our best near term shot at achieving a net-zero carbo=
n economy. For a full primer on fusion and the importance of this Q>1 achie=
vement, we recommend reading Lowercarbon Capital=E2=80=99s announcement of =
its $250M fund dedicated to nuclear fusion [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
cda3569f-c52e-4993-80d4-66535ea7a6d0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Turns out that Sacca guy [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/da19f013-abf8-489e-a280-1=
878a21d9264?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] knows what he=E2=80=99s doing =
with this whole investing thing.=20
(2) Renewables 2022 [ https://substack.com/redirect/50dc0b1b-1ac9-4cad-8531=
-b6c22f42f86a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ]
From the International Energy Agency
Renewables become the largest source of global electricity generation by ea=
rly 2025, surpassing coal. Their share of the power mix is forecast to incr=
ease by 10 percentage points over the forecast period, reaching 38% in 2027=
=2E Renewables are the only electricity g=
eneration source whose share is expe=
cted to grow, with declining shares for coal, natural gas, nuclear and oil =
generation. Electricity from wind and solar PV more than doubles in the nex=
t five years, providing almost 20% of global power generation in 2027.
Commercializing and scaling nuclear fusion is likely at least a decade or s=
o out, and in the meantime, we=E2=80=99ll be relying on renewable energy to=
 get us to a cleaner energy economy. The IEA issued a report forecasting th=
at renewables will be the largest source of electricity globally by 2025. T=
his latest report reflects an upwards revision on renewables, which are gro=
wing share much faster than expected just even a year ago.
Driving this change is faster than expected adoption of renewables from Chi=
na, the EU, the US, and India which are all quickly implementing and introd=
ucing policies in reaction to the energy crisis. The other major drivers ar=
e solar (which, thanks to learning curves, has become an economically feasi=
ble energy source in the last few years) and wind (which is expected to gro=
w more linearly over the coming years).
It=E2=80=99s tough to look at both the nuclear fusion breakthrough and the =
IEA renewables report and not be optimistic that we may just figure out thi=
s whole energy/climate thing sooner than most people would have thought jus=
t a few years ago. But there=E2=80=99s still a lot of work to be done.=20
(3) Stripe Frontier Q&A [ https://substack.com/redirect/9ff50062-d330-45b2-=
9f26-8aae7f673df3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ]
Q: What is carbon removal and why is it important?
A:  Humans emit about 50 billion tons of=C2=A0 CO=E2=82=82-equivalents ever=
y year. To avoid the worst effects of climate change, we need to get global=
 emissions to net zero emissions by 2050. That means broadly doing two thin=
gs.
First: radically reducing the amount of=C2=A0 CO=E2=82=82 we=E2=80=99re pum=
ping into the atmosphere every year.
Second: permanently removing huge amounts of carbon dioxide already in the =
atmosphere and ocean. Carbon removal is important both because it=E2=80=99s=
 unlikely we=E2=80=99ll be able to fully eliminate all sources of emissions=
, and because, even if we did, we=E2=80=99d still need to deal with the=C2=
=A0 CO=E2=82=82 that=E2=80=99s already in the atmosphere from the last 100+=
 years. Most climate models [ https://substack.com/redirect/c44e63ec-ac96-4=
97c-b8e3-3c0ce942738e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ] estimate we=E2=80=99ll need to remove around five to ten bi=
llion tons per year by 2050, roughly the equivalent of the United States=E2=
=80=99 annual emissions [ https://substack.com/redirect/3b792187-509b-424f-=
a7d4-690d52ba2e14?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ].
We=E2=80=99ve already done a fair amount of damage to our ecosystem. And ev=
en with new new, clean sources of energy, we=E2=80=99ll need to clean up th=
e mess we=E2=80=99ve already made. That=E2=80=99s where carbon removal come=
s into play.
We did a Q&A with Nan Ransohoff [ https://substack.com/redirect/ef59e9ca-55=
0a-43c8-8b5b-4628772f8474?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Head of Climate at Stripe, on carbon removal and Front=
ier=E2=80=99s approach to it. Just yesterday, Frontier announced its second=
 round of carbon removal purchases [ https://substack.com/redirect/7c68d03f=
-e8d1-42c0-9a62-dec3c2ffc18d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Stripe worked with three promising startups working on carbon removal to te=
ll their stories, and we=E2=80=99re sharing those videos below to give you =
a tangible sense of the breadth of approaches to carbon removal. Maybe it e=
ven motivates a few of you to tackle similarly ambitious projects or suppor=
t theirs.
Charm Industrial - Putting Oil Back Underground [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/8a3b2b4a-0fdc-4c76-8a5f-ecd6b25d195f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Mission Zero - Capturing CO=E2=82=82 from the Air [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/dc20f1a3-e6b8-4593-b1b7-6ccd91018ddf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Travertine - Converting CO=E2=82=82 into rocks [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/14828e31-b3bc-48b9-93ff-4323653f93ec?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
(4) Techno-optimism for 2023 [ https://substack.com/redirect/a97e36d5-08f2-=
4c34-b903-61f00daa5f92?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Noah Smith  [ https://substack.com/redirect/13658862-a354-42e4-ac61-82b5241=
0c65e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]f=
or Noahpinion
If you read the Weekly Dose of Optimism, you basically also read Noah Smith=
=E2=80=99s newsletter Noahpinion. That=E2=80=99s because we=E2=80=99re gene=
rally excited by and interested in many of the same topics and trends =E2=
=80=94 and because he=E2=80=99s one of the best writers on those topics and=
 trends, we often feature him. If you haven=E2=80=99t already, subscribe to=
 his newsletter.
In this recent essay, he maps out the three major areas of techno-optimism =
heading into 2023:
The A.I Breakout: =E2=80=9Cthe key reason to be optimistic about AI is that=
 it isn=E2=80=99t slowing down=E2=80=9D
The Energy Revolution Rolls Onward: =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re not just going t=
o save the planet from destruction; we=E2=80=99re going to get cheaper elec=
tricity than we have ever known, as a species=E2=80=9D
The Strange Biotech Boom: =E2=80=9Cthere is just a whole lot of human brain=
power going into a whole lot of different kinds of biotech, and it=E2=80=99=
s apparently paying off.=E2=80=9D
These are all topics we cover extensively at Not Boring, and we=E2=80=99d a=
dd in advancements in space, defense, manufacturing, and web3 infrastructur=
e as areas of optimism as we head into the new year.
(5) ChatGPT, Obesity Drugs, Exoplanet Images, and Medical Miracles: The Mos=
t Amazing Breakthroughs of 2022 [ https://substack.com/redirect/eaff3b81-a8=
f1-4771-bcb0-7f45148ffd08?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Derek Thompson and Eli Dourado for The Plain English Podcast
OK, we=E2=80=99re feeling the holiday spirit and giving shoutouts to all of=
 our fellow techno-optimist brothers out there. This conversation between D=
erek Thompson [ https://substack.com/redirect/bbc7b7c9-d633-4b1c-be3e-a89f8=
763e8d7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] and Eli Dourado [ https://substack.com/redirect/8693b30c-b56c-427c-9dd3-c=
20b3f8b32e9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ], both mainstays on the Weekly Dose of Optimism, covers much of the sa=
me ground as Smith=E2=80=99s essay, but is perhaps a bit more approachable =
for the uninitiated.
One interesting take away from this conversation is the recent the resurgen=
ce of obesity drugs. Fen-phen came on the market in the early 1990s and sub=
sequently withdrew in 1997, leaving a wake of $13B in legal damages and a n=
egative stigma around obesity drugs behind it. Now, Semaglutide, sold under=
 a variety of brand names (Wegovy, Ozempic, etc) is producing life altering=
 results [ https://substack.com/redirect/ec06a3e9-90ca-4424-9ad9-dba0035d6a=
b4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: ne=
arly 15% weight loss with minimal serious side effects.
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox 9am E=
ST on Monday morning with our last email of the year. Enjoy the weekend!
=E2=80=94 Packy

